President Kenyatta also rubbished claims that the BBI is aimed at creating additional seats for a select few, insisting that every Kenyan will have a chance to be represented and to contest for any position they wish to contest for regardless of their ethnicity, gender or race.





“What we are trying to achieve in Kenya is to ensure that no single Kenyan never again feels left out to the point that they want to become violent to achieve their objective,” he said.
Change the Constitution
“And that is why one of the critical components of the BBI is to ensure that we entrench in law bills that will ensure the youth are adequately catered for. And that is why we need the youth policy going out, so that we ensure the youth are at the centre of any developmental programmes in our country.”
The President said the quest to change the Constitution, had been informed by the cycle of election violence witnessed every voting year —a situation he said was catalysed by the winner take it all arrangement — but which had disenfranchised the youth, who were mostly used as conduits by the political elite to fan the violence.
The President said the BBI is not only aimed at addressing this problem by creating more seats that would be shared equitably, but also rope in the youth into positions of leadership and power. “We want our young people also involved in decision-making bodies all the way from county assemblies to the National Assembly.”



